WEBVTT

00:30.850 --> 00:32.332
Welcome to the Well Community Church.

00:32.372 --> 00:33.774
So glad you're hanging out with us here today.

00:33.794 --> 00:36.477
If you have your Bibles, we're going to be in 1st Samuel, chapter 12.

00:36.537 --> 00:38.880
If we have not met yet, my name is Brad.

00:38.900 --> 00:42.665
I'm one of the pastors here to get the privilege of handling God's Word here together.

00:42.745 --> 00:45.828
Something, by the way, that if you are a guest with us, this might be good for you to know.

00:45.868 --> 00:53.618
We here at the Well are very committed to our Bibles, very committed to teaching books of the Bible, many of which may be a bit

00:53.986 --> 01:13.009
I don't know, new to some, and so if for some reason you are new to the things of God or new to your Bible, the table of contents is your friend or Google it, but first Samuel chapter 12, we're continuing in a series called Monarchy where we're walking through three very unique Old Testament characters, King Saul, King David, and of course King Solomon.

01:13.729 --> 01:17.073
As we do jump in though, I just want to kind of catch up to speed as to where we've been.

01:17.194 --> 01:20.978
Last week we talked a little bit in chapters nine through 11,

01:21.090 --> 01:25.116
about King Saul who was a king who had no heart for God.

01:25.656 --> 01:33.287
And we saw in chapter 10 from last week that he was anointed to be king, this Saul, primarily because he had the right program stats.

01:33.868 --> 01:36.972
He was a big, strong, tough guy king who looked good on the outside.

01:37.913 --> 01:39.595
And so he is anointed to be king.

01:39.796 --> 01:45.343
And in chapter 10 verse 17, he's affirmed publicly and set into that role.

01:45.383 --> 01:47.346
And then of course, in chapter 11,

01:47.522 --> 01:53.549
He goes to work, and he does exactly what he was anointed king to do, which was to fight their battles.

01:54.190 --> 01:57.594
And the first battle that he fights is against a guy whose name is Nahash.

01:57.634 --> 01:58.495
It means snake.

01:59.016 --> 02:01.379
So he's the snake king of the Ammonites.

02:02.200 --> 02:10.169
And Saul rallies the nation to his side to go to war, sends out a tweet, 330,000 people reply.

02:10.209 --> 02:13.313
And there's a resounding victory.

02:14.394 --> 02:17.458
In chapter 11, verse 15, he's affirmed to be king.

02:17.730 --> 02:22.014
And it says, all the people now went to Gilgal and they all made sacrifices there.

02:23.176 --> 02:30.383
And King Saul was then anointed to be king and they offered sacrifices and peace offerings before the Lord.

02:30.443 --> 02:40.193
And there Saul and all the men of Israel rejoiced greatly and all seemed in that moment to be good on the outside.

02:40.814 --> 02:44.658
The problem with King Saul as we've discussed already previous

02:44.898 --> 02:51.227
is what was happening on the outside and what was happening on the inside were very, very different.

02:51.247 --> 02:56.754
And in fact, Mike introduced last week when he was teaching a concept called the sinkhole.

02:57.615 --> 03:02.162
It's really out of a book called Ordering Your Private World, written in 1984 by Gordon McDonald.

03:02.262 --> 03:03.263
Really interesting book.

03:03.684 --> 03:06.628
And in chapter one, he talks about the sinkhole syndrome.

03:06.648 --> 03:11.314
And this author makes the observation that in Florida, in times of extended drought,

03:11.522 --> 03:13.365
the aquifer underneath.

03:13.605 --> 03:21.577
So subterranean aquifer begins to dry out and it creates these literal caverns underneath the streets.

03:22.318 --> 03:27.406
On the outside, you would never even notice, but it's not uncommon in that region.

03:27.426 --> 03:40.466
Then after extended drought for entire streets to just disappear, for vehicles to get swallowed by the earth, for intersections, apartment complexes, you name it, it does not discriminate if that aquifer

03:40.546 --> 03:45.091
is gone underneath than whatever's on the surface is going to collapse.

03:45.151 --> 03:48.714
And in some ways, that's what happens with our guide, King Saul.

03:49.415 --> 03:51.217
And really, it's not just unique to him.

03:51.297 --> 04:02.208
Anytime your responsibilities out-seed your character or exceed your character, it's only a matter of time until a sinkhole of some sorts takes place in your life as well.

04:02.668 --> 04:08.114
And what we'll get into here in this week's message is the sinkholes now are beginning to show.

04:08.546 --> 04:16.875
And in verses, or chapters, rather 12 through 14, we'll talk about King Saul, a king who leads in the flesh.

04:17.536 --> 04:26.666
In chapter 12, Samuel's reflecting on his decision for a king and says in verse one of chapter 12, I gave you what you've wanted and I've walked before you.

04:26.706 --> 04:30.650
In some ways, kind of saying this is not my fault, this was your fault, you wanted this.

04:31.631 --> 04:37.618
And in verses 14 and 15, he says, look, if now you and your king fear God,

04:37.890 --> 04:39.712
things could go really well for you.

04:39.833 --> 04:45.520
God, God could use this even though this isn't what He commanded, it's not what He wanted, it's what you chose.

04:46.121 --> 04:49.205
If both you and the king fear God, it could go well.

04:49.245 --> 04:52.649
God could be, by His grace, redemptive in this and use it.

04:52.689 --> 05:00.920
But if not, verse 15, if you don't listen to the voice of the Lord and if you rebel against His commandments, then it's actually not gonna go well for you.

05:01.701 --> 05:05.586
And even though God in verses 19 and 20 was supposed to be

05:05.666 --> 05:08.891
your king, there's a chance that all might work out okay.

05:08.931 --> 05:20.129
And in fact, in verses 19 and 20, the people acknowledged the fact that they asked for something that the Lord didn't want, something that in verse 19, they call rather evil before God.

05:20.590 --> 05:22.533
And so they begged Samuel to pray for them.

05:23.494 --> 05:26.359
And Samuel says, yeah, I'm gonna pray for you, no problem.

05:26.379 --> 05:31.026
And God is gracious, and he may actually just use this for your benefit.

05:31.170 --> 05:41.186
in verse 20, because that's the kind of God he is, and he will not abandon you, verses 22 through 23, and he says, Samuel does, neither will I.

05:41.206 --> 05:50.221
And so before though we go any further in chapter 13 and get into the real nitty gritty of the story, we do have a bit of minor textual issue with verse one.

05:50.762 --> 05:54.128
Some of your Bibles are gonna show in verse one a textual note.

05:54.729 --> 05:58.034
Some of your Bibles may actually have the numbers in italics.

05:58.306 --> 06:04.575
Your Bible was originally written in Hebrew, a little bit of Aramaic and in Greek and then translated into English.

06:04.635 --> 06:08.440
And one of the most difficult things to translate is actually numbers.

06:08.460 --> 06:13.728
And so I'll show you a couple of different translation examples of verse one and why it's a bit of a minor issue.

06:14.329 --> 06:26.706
The New American Standard Bible, which is what I'm reading and maybe you have as well, says this in verse one, saw was 30 years old when he began to reign and he reigned 42 years over Israel.

06:27.138 --> 06:35.290
But the ESV says that Saul lived for one year and then became king and then he reigned for two years over Israel.

06:35.951 --> 06:37.753
And then the NIV says something else.

06:37.814 --> 06:43.902
It says Saul was 30 years old when he became king and he reigned over Israel for 42 years.

06:43.943 --> 06:47.728
So the question then is how old was he and how long did he reign?

06:48.289 --> 06:49.851
The good news is it doesn't really matter.

06:50.512 --> 06:54.578
Meaning there's really no theological implications as to which translation

06:54.690 --> 06:57.794
is correct, it doesn't change any theological meaning.

06:58.195 --> 07:03.702
It does ask some questions for us as to which is the correct way to take a look at this verse.

07:03.722 --> 07:08.128
And what it looks to be is that Saul was 40 years old when he began to reign.

07:08.829 --> 07:14.917
He reigned over Israel for two years when then the events of verse two began to occur.

07:15.638 --> 07:24.530
And so as we jump into the context here, what's gonna happen is previous battle against Nahash the snake king, 330 people rallied to Saul

07:25.154 --> 07:27.516
It was an incredible deliverance.

07:28.157 --> 07:38.788
But you can imagine that logistically and even just financially, keeping a mustard army of 330,000 troops is not just unnecessary, it's not realistic.

07:39.188 --> 07:47.196
And so what happens in verse two now is Saul is gonna choose 3,000 men to serve as a primary fighting force.

07:47.316 --> 07:48.958
2,000 are gonna go with Saul.

07:49.358 --> 07:53.202
A thousand of them are gonna go with Jonathan, his son.

07:53.666 --> 07:56.188
And Jonathan, in verse three, is gonna go pick a fight.

07:56.269 --> 08:04.757
Now, one of the things I hope you learned in this journey through Saul's life, as well as David's, is Jonathan should be on our list of heroes.

08:04.777 --> 08:05.718
This guy is crazy.

08:06.258 --> 08:10.582
So in verse three, this guy goes to pick a fight with the garrison of the Philistines that are at Giba.

08:11.183 --> 08:12.624
The Philistines heard about it.

08:13.665 --> 08:15.027
So now he's picked a fight.

08:15.047 --> 08:16.428
He's poked the bear, so to speak.

08:16.828 --> 08:21.693
Saul blows a trumpet and says, let all the Hebrews hear, we gotta go to war again.

08:21.753 --> 08:22.834
And in verse four,

08:23.074 --> 08:34.930
All Israel heard the news that Saul had smitten the garrison of the Philistines, and also that Israel had become odious to the Philistines, and so the people now are summoned to Saul, and so here we go again.

08:34.990 --> 08:41.039
The battle-ready king is now gonna have to go to war one more time.

08:41.499 --> 08:49.490
But in verse five, we have a problem, and the problem is this, he's gonna go to war, but remember now at the bottom of verse two,

08:49.698 --> 08:53.122
2,000 were with him, 1,000 were with his son, Jonathan.

08:53.202 --> 08:55.605
And then if you look at the bottom of verse two, everybody else went home.

08:56.366 --> 08:59.510
And so you don't have the same mustard army that you had before of 330,000.

09:00.171 --> 09:09.142
Strong, not only that, but in verse five, the Philistines are going to show up with 30,000 chariots and 6,000 horsemen.

09:09.663 --> 09:16.411
Now, true confession, I graduated from the California State University Fresno with a health degree.

09:16.972 --> 09:18.834
So math is not my strong suit.

09:19.042 --> 09:29.954
But I'm pretty sure when you got 3,000 people and they showed up with 36,000, 30,000 being chariots, 6,000 horsemen, that's not good math, okay?

09:30.314 --> 09:35.440
And so not only that, they are not just outnumbered, they are outgunned.

09:36.081 --> 09:41.667
So they've got 3,000 men and now 30,000 plus chariots and horsemen.

09:42.227 --> 09:44.249
And so it's gonna be an issue.

09:44.350 --> 09:48.434
Not only that, but the people around in verses six and seven

09:48.514 --> 09:49.875
They start doing the math too.

09:50.596 --> 09:59.526
And they saw that they were, my Bible says in a straight, verse six, some of your Bibles might say in trouble or in difficulty.

09:59.946 --> 10:03.930
The point is they're looking around, hey, bro, did you see how big those army were out there?

10:04.191 --> 10:08.936
Not only that, they look like the sand of the seashore, bottom of verse five.

10:08.996 --> 10:10.317
Like there's people everywhere.

10:10.497 --> 10:15.122
They got chariots, they got horsemen, I got a hula ho, this is not a good situation.

10:16.322 --> 10:23.932
And so sure enough, in verse six, it says the people began to hide themselves in caves and in thickets, in cliffs and in cellars and in pits.

10:24.493 --> 10:31.723
And then in verse seven, some of those even now driven by fear and cowardice run and flee the country.

10:32.484 --> 10:38.733
But Saul, he was still in Gilgal and all the people who followed him followed him trembling.

10:39.213 --> 10:40.795
Saul's got a leadership crisis.

10:41.416 --> 10:42.738
He's got a problem on his hands.

10:43.138 --> 10:47.384
From a very practical point of view, he's losing the battle of momentum.

10:48.025 --> 10:52.190
If any of you in athletics ever experienced momentum, it's a swing.

10:52.210 --> 10:56.876
I mean, there are just times athletically where momentum is on your side.

10:56.896 --> 10:58.519
It doesn't matter what you do it works.

10:59.660 --> 11:09.433
I mean, you might be in a competition and you call them the worst play for that moment you could ever call, but for some reason it just hits and then you've probably been on the other side.

11:09.894 --> 11:12.978
Or it doesn't matter what you do, it just seems like it doesn't work.

11:13.186 --> 11:14.487
because momentum is shifting.

11:14.808 --> 11:21.034
And Saul is a good enough leader pragmatically that he notices this, and he knows we've got a problem.

11:21.394 --> 11:24.697
If we don't move very, very quickly, things are gonna get awry.

11:24.877 --> 11:28.281
Now, here's the problem with momentum-driven leaders.

11:29.222 --> 11:36.849
Is they tend to think it's all about them, and they don't acknowledge the mystery of what God might be doing above and beyond all of it.

11:37.309 --> 11:42.034
So Psalm 127 says, unless the Lord build the city, the laborer's labor in vain who build it,

11:42.338 --> 11:45.842
Unless the Lord watch over the city, the watchman stays awake and vain.

11:45.902 --> 11:51.488
It's a vain thing for a driven leader to stay up late or rise early or eat the bread of painful labor.

11:51.528 --> 11:51.729
Why?

11:51.769 --> 11:55.152
Because the Lord gives to his beloved even while they sleep.

11:55.933 --> 12:09.128
And so what's happening here is you've got a very driven leader, a very pragmatic leader, a very momentum oriented leader who's realizing we need to go and we need to go now.

12:09.328 --> 12:10.770
Now the problem with that

12:10.978 --> 12:12.520
is that Samuel said to wait.

12:13.681 --> 12:14.422
Now, who is Samuel?

12:14.803 --> 12:17.566
Samuel is like the spiritual anchor of these people.

12:17.986 --> 12:30.141
So you had a lowercase K King Saul, who was supposed to submit to an uppercase K King God, and the spiritual side of things was taken care of rather by Samuel.

12:30.742 --> 12:34.746
Samuel, by the way, his name comes from one of two words, L means God.

12:36.168 --> 12:37.810
Shem means name.

12:38.146 --> 12:41.609
or it could come from Shema, which means to hear or to listen.

12:41.930 --> 12:48.496
So Samuel's name could be the name or his name is God, or he listens or hears God.

12:48.656 --> 12:53.021
Either way, his namesake simply means God's presence there.

12:53.401 --> 12:58.606
Samuel was the prophet, Samuel was the priest, Samuel told Saul, wait for me.

12:59.167 --> 13:00.588
We are the people of God.

13:00.949 --> 13:02.530
We don't go to war without him.

13:03.551 --> 13:06.354
And so don't get pragmatic on me, wait.

13:06.434 --> 13:11.760
I'm coming, we'll offer a sacrifice, then we'll go and we'll fight these battles.

13:12.321 --> 13:12.601
Why?

13:12.621 --> 13:15.905
Because the Lord does not delight in the strength of horses.

13:16.566 --> 13:18.849
The Lord does not take pleasure in the legs of men.

13:19.229 --> 13:22.533
The Lord favors those who fear him, those who wait for his loving kindness.

13:22.594 --> 13:24.756
That's who we are as the people of God.

13:25.197 --> 13:27.520
So calm down, driven leader, wait for me.

13:28.320 --> 13:29.862
Verse eight, he can't wait.

13:31.524 --> 13:36.210
He waited seven days according to the appointed times set by Samuel, but Samuel did not come to Gilgal.

13:36.514 --> 13:38.597
And so the people all scattered before him.

13:39.078 --> 13:43.786
And so Saul said, bring me the burn offering and the peace offering and he offered the burn offerings.

13:43.866 --> 13:48.274
And as soon as he had finished the burn offerings, behold, Samuel came.

13:48.534 --> 13:49.516
Isn't that like the Lord?

13:50.317 --> 13:52.240
I mean, God's like, just wait for me.

13:52.280 --> 13:54.283
And so he's waiting and he's waiting and he's waiting.

13:54.304 --> 13:55.485
He's like, I can't take it anymore.

13:55.506 --> 13:56.547
He offers a sacrifice.

13:56.607 --> 14:03.058
And in that moment, Samuel shows up and it says that Saul went out to meet him and to greet him.

14:03.842 --> 14:09.329
Any of you have kids and your kids greet you at the door and you're like, what did you do?

14:09.389 --> 14:17.279
That was one time my brother and I got sideways and he decided to come after me with a wiffle ball bat and boy, he lit me up good.

14:17.740 --> 14:25.389
But we had a long driveway and he saw my mom coming home down the driveway and so he greeted mom at the front door, hey mom, what are you doing home early?

14:25.489 --> 14:29.234
I mean, it just screamed felony, written all over his face, right?

14:29.730 --> 14:31.673
And so, sure enough, that's what this seems like.

14:31.713 --> 14:41.368
Here's Saul who goes and greets Samuel and listen to Saul's inability to take responsibility for what he did, verses 11 and following.

14:41.388 --> 14:43.571
He says, Samuel says to him, what have you done?

14:43.611 --> 14:50.261
And Saul says, look, I saw that the people were scattering from me and you didn't come within the appointed time.

14:50.321 --> 14:53.426
And meanwhile, the Philistines were assembling, you know,

14:53.570 --> 14:59.796
And so therefore I said, look, the Philistines are gonna come down against me and I'm unprepared for this.

14:59.916 --> 15:02.038
And what happens if they attacked me?

15:02.078 --> 15:04.320
And I haven't even asked for the favor of the Lord yet.

15:04.901 --> 15:10.326
And so I forced myself and I offered the burnt offerings.

15:12.008 --> 15:13.790
So it's probably their fault.

15:13.890 --> 15:15.752
It's most likely your fault.

15:15.812 --> 15:17.213
It's most certainly their fault.

15:17.393 --> 15:18.815
Let me tell you whose fault it's not.

15:19.635 --> 15:21.257
It is not my fault, okay?

15:21.277 --> 15:22.418
You're the one who is late.

15:22.978 --> 15:24.480
You're the one who didn't show up on time.

15:24.500 --> 15:29.307
And so therefore I, I forced myself to do what I wasn't supposed to do.

15:30.028 --> 15:37.339
And so sure enough, in verses 13 and 14, that rash decision is going to have dire consequences.

15:37.379 --> 15:38.901
By the way, that's the thing with sin.

15:39.943 --> 15:42.707
When we sin, it usually takes us farther than we want to go.

15:42.767 --> 15:47.474
It costs us more than we want to pay and usually impacts more people.

15:47.586 --> 15:49.188
then we would ever care to impact.

15:49.208 --> 15:50.049
And look at what happens.

15:50.429 --> 15:53.734
He says in verse 13, you have acted foolishly, correct?

15:54.334 --> 15:56.877
You have not kept the commandment of the Lord, correct?

15:58.519 --> 16:02.684
God would have established your kingdom over Israel forever.

16:02.745 --> 16:10.514
Had you just been a lower case-k king who submitted to the upper case-k king of kings in Lord of Lords, but you couldn't do that, could you?

16:11.475 --> 16:12.697
You couldn't wait for God.

16:12.757 --> 16:14.058
You couldn't submit to God.

16:14.319 --> 16:15.560
You had to have it your way.

16:15.620 --> 16:17.042
And because of that verse 14,

16:17.890 --> 16:19.092
Your kingdom will not endure.

16:19.733 --> 16:24.519
The Lord has sought out now for himself a man after his own heart.

16:25.160 --> 16:30.267
And the Lord has appointed him ruler over his people because you have not kept the Lord's command.

16:30.968 --> 16:34.653
And sure enough, God's gonna go and find a young shepherd boy by the name of David.

16:35.154 --> 16:40.061
David is gonna be called a man after God's own heart, still a scoundrel, but a man after God's own heart.

16:40.782 --> 16:43.986
And because of his rash,

16:44.162 --> 16:46.766
pragmatism, Saul misses the opportunity.

16:47.247 --> 16:49.290
Well, the battle in chapter 13 continues.

16:49.370 --> 16:54.978
The enemy gets divided into three different camps, Saul's army being poorly armed.

16:55.579 --> 16:57.041
All they've got is farm equipment.

16:57.181 --> 17:00.787
The only people with swords are Samuel and Jonathan or a Saul rather in Jonathan.

17:01.368 --> 17:05.454
So like I mentioned earlier, you got hula hose and shovels going to war.

17:06.495 --> 17:11.122
And in chapter 14, Jonathan is going to go do what Jonathan does.

17:11.394 --> 17:13.196
I mentioned already, Jonathan's nuts.

17:13.216 --> 17:19.263
Do any of you have a son, by the way, who when, like your neighbor's like, hey, you're never going to guess what your son just did?

17:19.323 --> 17:20.244
And you're like, oh, great.

17:21.285 --> 17:22.146
What do you do this time?

17:22.266 --> 17:23.567
You know, he jumped off a what?

17:23.788 --> 17:25.149
You know, into what?

17:26.330 --> 17:29.474
And that's, I think, what Jonathan is like.

17:29.494 --> 17:32.297
I think Jonathan is the kind of guy who's like, you don't know how to do.

17:33.799 --> 17:36.982
Let's go climb that hill and let's kill those 20 guys.

17:37.803 --> 17:40.466
And his armor bearer, who's with him, is like, let's go.

17:40.706 --> 17:42.769
And so that's what happens in chapter 14.

17:43.109 --> 17:52.481
They climb the hill into the Philistine camp, and they fight and kill 20 dudes, and confusion sets in the camp.

17:52.501 --> 17:56.666
Because meanwhile, on the other side of the hill, Saul is watching what's happening over there.

17:56.686 --> 17:58.028
He's like, what's going on over there?

17:58.408 --> 18:02.554
And he can see the confusion that's beginning to stir across the hill.

18:03.114 --> 18:06.098
And he starts looking around and goes, do the math, who's missing?

18:06.178 --> 18:08.201
One, two, three, four, five, six.

18:08.221 --> 18:19.316
He starts looking around, sure enough, verse 17, Jonathan is the one who now is missing and he realizes the problem that's happening over there, it's Jonathan.

18:19.336 --> 18:20.077
He's done it again.

18:21.078 --> 18:29.930
And so in that, he's a little nervous because his son's over there, he's outnumbered, he doesn't know what's going on, he just knows there's a bit of chaos happening.

18:30.331 --> 18:32.995
And so in verses 18 and 19, look at what he asks for.

18:33.375 --> 18:35.538
He asks Ahijah the priest,

18:35.618 --> 18:37.582
to bring him the arc of God.

18:38.303 --> 18:39.365
Now, what's the arc of God?

18:39.385 --> 18:41.529
Well, we first saw the arc in the book of Exodus.

18:41.609 --> 18:45.857
When Moses leads the people out of Egypt, there's a box.

18:45.977 --> 18:55.314
It's like a cedar chest, like a hope chest, really, that God creates, very ornate, but it's to kind of be the symbol of the presence of God.

18:55.682 --> 19:00.608
Inside that ark is gonna be the 10 commandments from the tablets that Moses collects.

19:00.749 --> 19:08.519
There's gonna be Aaron's rod that had butted to affirm his leadership and then like a Tupperware of manna is in there.

19:09.019 --> 19:13.265
And when the presence of God descended, it descended over the ark of the covenant.

19:13.625 --> 19:17.070
And so it was kind of affirming God's presence among the people.

19:18.091 --> 19:20.574
But he says, go bring now the ark of God here.

19:20.594 --> 19:23.698
What is God now a lucky charm?

19:24.546 --> 19:25.888
Like, is this a rabbit's foot?

19:25.908 --> 19:30.736
Like, when did the Ark of God ever get brought into battle?

19:30.776 --> 19:44.537
Well, actually, previous in chapter six of this very book where the Ark of God gets taken by the Philistines, this very enemy, ends up making the rounds through the Philistine cities while God just wrecks all of the people there with tumors.

19:44.637 --> 19:45.278
It's beautiful.

19:45.478 --> 19:46.440
They'll get hemorrhoids.

19:46.460 --> 19:47.762
It's a wonderful story.

19:49.090 --> 19:50.351
And God delivers himself.

19:50.571 --> 19:53.254
They find day gone, their God on its face beheaded.

19:53.274 --> 20:00.481
I mean, it's beautiful because God's like, okay, you don't bring me here like I'm some sort of trinket.

20:00.501 --> 20:02.083
Well, that's what he seems to do.

20:02.103 --> 20:03.965
Now on the outside, you go, okay.

20:04.545 --> 20:06.047
Let's make sure God is in the midst.

20:06.067 --> 20:07.308
Go get the Ark of God.

20:07.348 --> 20:09.190
Let's bring God here.

20:10.271 --> 20:14.195
And it says, for that time, the Ark of God was with the sons of Israel.

20:14.235 --> 20:17.778
But in verse 19, while Saul talked to the priest,

20:18.114 --> 20:23.561
He's watching the commotion in the camp of the Philistines across the way where you know his son's picking a fight.

20:23.581 --> 20:26.324
And it says that the commotion continues to increase.

20:26.344 --> 20:29.207
So Saul said to the priest, withdraw your hand.

20:30.249 --> 20:35.335
So even if we give him credit, which I'm not willing to give him credit, that this was a good thing to bring the ark there.

20:35.595 --> 20:37.738
He doesn't have the patience to finish what he started.

20:38.559 --> 20:41.342
He brings the ark there and he's like, all right, forget it, let's go.

20:41.843 --> 20:44.126
And so off to battle now they go.

20:44.867 --> 20:47.730
And in verse 20, Saul and all the people who are with him,

20:48.386 --> 20:49.932
rallied and came to the battle.

20:50.273 --> 20:51.980
Now what did they find when they got there?

20:52.522 --> 20:59.570
Behold, every man's sword was against his fellow, and there there was a great, a very great confusion.

20:59.650 --> 21:04.897
Johnathan came up with his armor bearer, they killed 20 dudes, and then panic breaks out in the camp of the Philistines.

21:05.298 --> 21:14.270
To the point where these guys don't know who's who, next thing you know, this guy's killing his neighbor, killing his brother, killing his uncle, and Johnathan and his armor bearer just watching it probably go down.

21:14.590 --> 21:18.996
Here comes Saul in the army to show up to rescue them, but God didn't need their rescue.

21:19.838 --> 21:22.882
God had things well in hand in the battle that was taking place there.

21:23.543 --> 21:26.066
And in verse 21 it says the Hebrews now,

21:26.466 --> 21:35.419
who were with the Philistines previously, who went up with them all around in the camp, even they turned to be with the Israelites who were with Saul and Jonathan.

21:35.860 --> 21:40.146
And in verse 22, even the ones that were all hiding out in the fields, they start showing up.

21:41.568 --> 21:44.432
And now they pursue them closely in battle.

21:44.793 --> 21:49.680
And in verse 23, it says, so that Saul delivered Israel that day.

21:49.780 --> 21:50.761
Is that what your Bible says?

21:51.523 --> 21:53.906
Verse 23, Saul delivered

21:54.114 --> 21:55.015
Israel that day.

21:55.055 --> 21:56.296
No, it's not what mine says either.

21:56.356 --> 21:58.078
Saul didn't deliver anybody.

21:58.879 --> 22:02.983
It says, so now the Lord delivered Israel that day.

22:03.043 --> 22:03.243
Why?

22:03.664 --> 22:06.586
Because God is the one who fights her battles.

22:06.606 --> 22:12.072
And he didn't need Saul to do what Saul did, but Saul did it anyway.

22:12.092 --> 22:16.797
Now, he's sensing Saul is in this moment that momentum's on his side.

22:17.617 --> 22:22.162
And so in verse 24, he makes a really strange and rash vow.

22:22.786 --> 22:37.063
And it says to the men of Israel who were hard pressed on that day, saw he says, put them under an oath saying, cursed be any man who eats food before evening and until I have avenged myself on my enemies.

22:38.025 --> 22:40.127
So none of the people tasted any food.

22:40.147 --> 22:41.088
Now this makes no sense.

22:41.589 --> 22:47.516
This reminds me of when I was playing football in Fresno in high school in the summer.

22:48.658 --> 22:52.242
It's like 140 degrees because we're in Mojave here.

22:52.450 --> 22:54.172
At least it felt like that.

22:54.212 --> 22:56.575
And you're trying not to pass out from heat stroke.

22:56.975 --> 23:00.379
And back then, we didn't know as much about hydration, I guess, as we do today.

23:00.619 --> 23:05.124
And they would say, hey, look, we're not stopping for a water break until you get it right.

23:05.645 --> 23:07.707
I'm thinking, I can't even spell my own name right now.

23:07.747 --> 23:09.148
I'm just hoping not to fall down.

23:09.769 --> 23:15.956
What probably would have been best is go get you some water, catch your breath a little bit, then let's come get it right.

23:16.056 --> 23:18.479
And everybody probably would have functioned at a higher level.

23:18.879 --> 23:21.522
But in this moment, Saul can't have that.

23:21.634 --> 23:22.615
He's got momentum.

23:22.635 --> 23:24.558
He's like, no Chipotle runs, okay?

23:24.818 --> 23:25.940
Nobody slows down.

23:26.341 --> 23:27.843
Nobody gets a little sandwich.

23:27.963 --> 23:28.343
Nothing.

23:28.664 --> 23:29.685
We keep pressing.

23:29.725 --> 23:30.607
We keep fighting.

23:30.667 --> 23:31.548
We keep pushing.

23:31.848 --> 23:33.531
We outwork, outlast.

23:34.131 --> 23:36.114
We now go.

23:36.655 --> 23:37.536
Nobody's stopping.

23:37.636 --> 23:44.987
Now you can just feel the drive coming from this leader because he doesn't want to lose momentum.

23:45.567 --> 23:46.769
And then comes verse 25.

23:46.949 --> 23:50.354
It says, all the people now had entered the forest

23:50.946 --> 23:52.708
And there was honey on the ground.

23:52.788 --> 23:56.933
God had graciously provided them like a goopack.

23:56.953 --> 23:58.234
Do you ever ride bicycles?

23:59.055 --> 24:05.623
There was a season where I used to ride bicycles with Mike Sladen, but I valued our friendship too much because he kept taking.

24:05.643 --> 24:07.725
He took me to the top of the four lane on a bike.

24:08.426 --> 24:10.288
If I could have caught him, I would have killed him.

24:10.389 --> 24:11.730
I hated him.

24:11.750 --> 24:15.154
But you would carry food, you know, and you'd carry these little goopacks.

24:15.394 --> 24:17.337
And it's basically like a little honey pack like this.

24:17.377 --> 24:18.118
Think of what God did.

24:18.398 --> 24:25.869
God provided for them a little snack along the way, re-nourish, brighten your eyes a little bit, and then we'll get back to the battle here.

24:26.530 --> 24:30.175
But because Saul had made that rash vow, they all pass it up.

24:30.696 --> 24:36.644
But look at verse 27, but Jonathan had not heard of the vow that his father had put them under.

24:38.046 --> 24:43.794
So Jonathan passes by the honey, puts the end of his staff in the ground, takes a little swipe of honey,

24:43.938 --> 24:48.285
takes a little bite, and in the bottom of verse 27, his eyes brighten.

24:48.305 --> 24:49.446
Yes, of course they brighten.

24:49.486 --> 24:50.788
He had a nice little snack.

24:51.730 --> 24:53.773
Okay, now he's better prepared for the battle.

24:54.654 --> 25:01.124
But in verse 28, they say, hey, look, your father had strictly put us under no thing that cursed is the man who eats any food this day.

25:01.184 --> 25:05.250
So now you've directly gone against a commandment of the king, your father.

25:06.112 --> 25:09.797
And he acknowledges, Jonathan does, what silliness that was in 29 and 30.

25:09.817 --> 25:11.280
He's like, why did he do that?

25:11.380 --> 25:12.882
Why did he trouble us with that?

25:13.346 --> 25:20.637
that the victory would have been even more profound had we had a chance to stop and to eat, but instead he made this foolish vow.

25:20.737 --> 25:22.099
Like why would he do that?

25:22.940 --> 25:29.149
And in verses 31 and following, they struck the Philistines now from Macmesh to I alone.

25:29.810 --> 25:40.626
The people were very weary and so weary that this vow that Saul put them under this rash vow

25:40.866 --> 25:49.739
that he put them under, it leads them in verse 32 and it even furthers him because now they're killing the livestock and just eating it with the blood in it, which was contrary to the law of God.

25:49.759 --> 25:55.067
So like one foolish decision is now leading to more and more foolishness down the road.

25:55.528 --> 25:57.511
Now in verse 35, Saul tries to make it right.

25:57.992 --> 26:00.656
And if you look at verse 35, he builds an altar to the Lord.

26:00.696 --> 26:04.501
But as you look at verse 35, is there anything interesting about that verse to you?

26:05.663 --> 26:10.290
It's the first time he's ever built an altar to the Lord.

26:10.370 --> 26:12.092
You could say, I mean, this is good.

26:12.152 --> 26:13.493
He's building an altar to the Lord.

26:13.513 --> 26:15.655
And then you realize, he's never done this before.

26:16.196 --> 26:17.277
This is performative.

26:18.298 --> 26:21.701
This is Saul trying to be someone he's not.

26:22.642 --> 26:26.346
This is Saul trying to, well, I really stepped on a rake with this one.

26:26.386 --> 26:27.327
How do I make this right?

26:27.347 --> 26:28.027
You know what I'll do?

26:28.548 --> 26:30.169
I'll build an altar to the Lord.

26:30.590 --> 26:32.351
That'll fix everything.

26:32.371 --> 26:36.455
And he inquires in verse 37 of the priests.

26:37.517 --> 26:39.058
And he says, well, shall I go down?

26:39.906 --> 26:43.950
and go after the Philistines, will you give them into my hand?

26:44.571 --> 26:47.795
But you'll notice in verse 37, the Lord does not answer him.

26:48.155 --> 26:51.038
Because that's not really a prayer, that's permission asking.

26:52.019 --> 26:54.762
That's not really asking Lord, what do you want here this day?

26:54.802 --> 26:57.004
That's saying, hey Lord, this is what I wanna do.

26:57.265 --> 26:59.727
Are you gonna bless my plans or not?

27:00.028 --> 27:01.449
And the Lord's like, I don't answer to you.

27:01.930 --> 27:04.432
And so he doesn't give him a word at that point.

27:04.993 --> 27:09.618
And then in verses 38 and following, we know that there's a problem.

27:10.050 --> 27:12.733
Saul begins to realize God's not answering me.

27:14.095 --> 27:16.017
Somebody must have broke my vow.

27:16.658 --> 27:17.659
Somebody did something.

27:18.100 --> 27:21.063
Certainly, I mean, still, you talk about lack of self-awareness.

27:21.524 --> 27:22.124
Couldn't be me.

27:22.925 --> 27:23.886
Must be somebody else.

27:24.627 --> 27:33.618
And so he says in verse 39, for as the Lord lives, whoever delivers Israel, though it would be Jonathan my son, he shall surely die.

27:34.082 --> 27:41.249
So whoever it is that broke my vow, whoever it is that disobeyed God, whoever it is that did whatever they did, we're gonna find out who did it.

27:41.990 --> 27:47.415
And when I find out who did it, I'm gonna kill him, even if it's my son.

27:47.435 --> 27:49.237
And so they end up casting lots.

27:49.777 --> 27:50.978
Think of it like flipping a coin.

27:50.998 --> 27:52.500
Like is it somebody from this side of the room?

27:52.520 --> 27:54.482
But that's how the room like, oh, I guess it's you guys.

27:54.942 --> 27:56.484
Is it from that aisle or this aisle?

27:56.564 --> 27:57.204
Oh, I guess it's here.

27:57.685 --> 28:02.930
And it narrows it down into what's, it's all on one side and Jonathan

28:03.138 --> 28:06.201
on the other, and the cast is given now to Jonathan.

28:06.902 --> 28:08.684
And so we know that it's him.

28:10.105 --> 28:14.770
And in verse 43, Saul says then, it says to Jonathan, well, tell me what you've done.

28:16.291 --> 28:21.116
And Jonathan says, well, look, I tasted a little honey at the end of my staff that was in my hand.

28:22.297 --> 28:23.238
I guess I should die.

28:24.720 --> 28:26.241
I mean, it seems a little overkill, don't you think?

28:27.102 --> 28:31.026
And then Saul says, well, and you can just kind of hear the sword unsheaving.

28:31.586 --> 28:38.474
And he says, well, may God do this to me and more also, for you shall surely die Jonathan.

28:38.494 --> 28:39.895
Now, does that make sense to you?

28:40.856 --> 28:45.401
Like, here's this guy, he tasted a little bit of honey in the king's like, yep, I guess you got to go, buddy.

28:45.962 --> 28:46.683
His own son.

28:47.544 --> 28:54.431
And thankfully in verse 45, the people that hear this going down are like, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, like this is crazy.

28:54.912 --> 28:57.074
And they step in and intervene.

28:57.506 --> 29:01.631
And we'll see as it comes to Saul's life, and we'll cover this next week.

29:02.032 --> 29:05.617
His biggest concern is not his lack of relationship with God.

29:06.117 --> 29:10.984
His biggest concern is his diminished popularity with the people, and we'll cover that next week.

29:11.564 --> 29:16.751
What I'd like to do is kind of see if we can pull some practical insights from this text as we bring it to a close.

29:17.472 --> 29:25.042
It's interesting that Saul has no heart for God, but hindsight's 2020 in that I don't think we should have been surprised by that.

29:25.186 --> 29:28.751
because I don't think he's had a heart for God from the very beginning.

29:29.272 --> 29:36.583
So when it comes to Saul's life, back in chapter nine, do you remember he's on a rescue mission sent by his father to go find their lost donkeys?

29:37.304 --> 29:38.386
And they can't seem to find him.

29:38.826 --> 29:40.829
So he's like, well, my father's gonna start freaking out.

29:40.849 --> 29:41.510
So let's go home.

29:42.592 --> 29:46.457
And the guy who's with him, he says, you know, there's a man of God in this area.

29:46.498 --> 29:49.762
Maybe we should go acquire or inquire rather of him.

29:49.963 --> 29:50.804
And he's like, oh, there is.

29:51.465 --> 29:53.007
Well, yeah, we should totally do that then, I guess.

29:53.228 --> 29:54.930
He didn't even know who Samuel was.

29:55.298 --> 29:57.060
Well, I think that's interesting.

29:57.080 --> 30:08.813
In chapter 10, the spirit of God comes upon Saul and Saul ends up among the prophets, like prophesying, quoting his Bible, maybe, we don't know, it just says he's prophesying.

30:09.173 --> 30:11.416
And his high school buddies are like, dude, is that Saul?

30:11.776 --> 30:12.757
Who's like, what the prophets?

30:13.018 --> 30:20.626
Like five minutes ago he was doing a cake stand, now he's hanging out with the prophets, that's weird, I don't remember him being like that.

30:20.962 --> 30:27.012
And then in chapter 14 verse 35, he's gonna build that altar to the Lord, but again, it's the first one he's ever built.

30:27.092 --> 30:33.442
My point is, I don't think Saul has ever really demonstrated a heart for God.

30:34.244 --> 30:37.469
On the outside, maybe, but it felt performative.

30:37.609 --> 30:39.372
On the inside, I don't think so.

30:39.412 --> 30:41.315
And here's a couple of other indicators.

30:42.277 --> 30:48.146
It's interesting to me that you don't ever really see him pray, like pray.

30:48.802 --> 30:51.766
Do you see him ask God if God will bless his battle plans?

30:51.826 --> 30:52.867
Yes, but that's not praying.

30:53.148 --> 30:57.974
That's like saying, before I eat, there was that one time I prayed.

30:59.156 --> 31:00.398
And then saying that that's praying.

31:00.418 --> 31:01.139
That's different.

31:01.159 --> 31:03.241
That's asking God to bless your stuff.

31:03.281 --> 31:03.822
That's different.

31:04.443 --> 31:11.352
When you read, for example, David, who's the next king will cover, the king after God's own heart.

31:11.913 --> 31:15.698
David says in Psalm 13, consider and answer me, or God,

31:16.162 --> 31:19.086
In light my eyes or I will sleep the sleep of death.

31:19.106 --> 31:21.429
My enemy will be exalted over me.

31:22.010 --> 31:28.659
My adversary will rejoice when I am shaken, but I have trusted in your loving kindness.

31:29.320 --> 31:31.383
My heart will rejoice in your salvation.

31:31.503 --> 31:34.807
I will sing to the Lord because you have dealt bountifully with me.

31:35.128 --> 31:35.669
That's prayer.

31:36.930 --> 31:39.634
Prayer is being with God in a way.

31:40.194 --> 31:49.008
that allows you to communicate, yes, your heart and thoughts, but also to receive from God the truth of who he is, and you never see Saul pray.

31:49.609 --> 31:51.712
He never seeks God.

31:52.554 --> 32:01.889
And in some ways, you almost feel like he feels like he should, but there's a difference between your authentic self and your ideal self.

32:02.650 --> 32:07.698
See, the ideal self is the you that you think others want you to be, or the you that you think you should be,

32:07.842 --> 32:12.268
Or that you think God might even want you to be, but it may not be authentically you.

32:13.109 --> 32:16.815
And it's like putting somebody else's clothes on it, it just kind of feels uncomfortable.

32:17.415 --> 32:19.739
Godliness to Saul feels uncomfortable.

32:19.759 --> 32:19.919
Why?

32:20.199 --> 32:22.643
Because Saul's used to doing what Saul wants to do.

32:23.263 --> 32:25.066
Saul wants to be the capital K King.

32:25.086 --> 32:26.408
He doesn't want to submit to God.

32:26.949 --> 32:27.910
And so he doesn't pray.

32:28.050 --> 32:33.057
Second, you never see Saul associated at all with the Bible.

32:34.379 --> 32:36.562
So for example, in Deuteronomy 17,

32:36.802 --> 32:39.477
God told Moses, look, the people are going to want a king one day.

32:39.517 --> 32:40.764
I know that's in their hearts.

32:40.864 --> 32:41.488
I get that.

32:42.332 --> 32:44.082
When they pick a king,

32:44.418 --> 32:50.404
One of the things that king should do is translate a copy of his Bible in the presence of the priest to make sure it's accurate.

32:50.824 --> 32:57.411
And that king should spend time on the regular in his Bible, reading the Bible and letting the Bible read him.

32:57.511 --> 33:01.655
Because if that king wants to flourish as a king, he's got to learn to submit to me.

33:01.935 --> 33:05.118
And the only way he'll learn to submit to me is to understand my word.

33:05.158 --> 33:07.700
He needs to read his Bible, let his Bible read him.

33:08.501 --> 33:10.243
Number one responsibility for a king.

33:10.463 --> 33:12.025
Do you ever see Saul read his Bible?

33:13.146 --> 33:13.426
No.

33:13.986 --> 33:15.628
Do you ever see him quote his Bible?

33:16.469 --> 33:16.669
No.

33:17.470 --> 33:19.552
Do you ever see him refer to the Bible at all?

33:19.712 --> 33:22.355
Well, in the Word of God, it says, misquoted even.

33:22.735 --> 33:22.955
No.

33:23.976 --> 33:24.156
No.

33:24.256 --> 33:26.719
Do you ever see him write any of the Bible?

33:26.919 --> 33:27.940
May you say, write the Bible?

33:27.980 --> 33:28.741
Well, think about this.

33:29.181 --> 33:31.244
Most of the songs were written by King David.

33:32.044 --> 33:34.267
Most of the Proverbs were written by King Solomon.

33:34.987 --> 33:39.792
And yet, Saul, no interaction with his Bible whatsoever.

33:40.673 --> 33:41.554
And then finally,

33:41.954 --> 33:47.901
Saul seems to be a leader just by observation, a leader who lives in the flesh.

33:48.322 --> 33:50.685
He leads in the flesh.

33:50.885 --> 33:51.987
Now, let me tell you what I mean by that.

33:52.007 --> 33:53.308
I don't mean indulgence.

33:54.209 --> 33:56.112
I don't mean he's a leader who's immoral.

33:56.172 --> 33:57.273
That's not what I'm suggesting.

33:58.074 --> 34:01.098
To lead in the flesh means that he leads in autonomy.

34:01.999 --> 34:06.605
He leads by instinct, gut, metrics.

34:06.625 --> 34:08.367
He leads pragmatically.

34:08.848 --> 34:10.610
He's leading based on momentum.

34:11.074 --> 34:22.854
He's leading based on his leadership instinct, his drive, momentum, all of these things that many people lead by, solves driven by that.

34:22.914 --> 34:37.618
Now the problem with that is the scripture's gonna invite us to trust in the Lord with all of our heart to lean not on our own understanding, but in all of our ways to acknowledge him and he'll make our past straight to not be wise in our own estimations.

34:38.242 --> 34:40.265
but to fear the Lord and to turn away from evil.

34:40.325 --> 34:42.888
And yet, Saul seems to be the opposite.

34:42.968 --> 34:45.511
Now, why is a text like this here?

34:45.571 --> 34:46.653
Well, let me just ask you.

34:46.673 --> 34:47.394
I'm curious.

34:48.595 --> 34:54.563
Do you know of anybody in your life who does life very pragmatically, practically?

34:55.624 --> 34:58.247
Who, if I said to you, hey, tell me about their prayer life.

34:58.287 --> 35:00.871
They don't seek God.

35:00.931 --> 35:03.474
They don't pray very frequently.

35:03.650 --> 35:10.059
Maybe now and again for a meal, but they're not sitting in God's presence, allowing relational connection to the Lord.

35:10.760 --> 35:13.403
Their time and their Bible is few and far between.

35:13.464 --> 35:15.947
They don't really read their Bible.

35:16.648 --> 35:23.658
It's even more infrequent for the Bible to ever read them, which means then they lead in flesh.

35:24.579 --> 35:26.061
They lead in autonomy.

35:26.542 --> 35:32.690
Do you know of anybody else in your life who can go an hour and never even think about God?

35:34.626 --> 35:36.648
Who might go half a day or a day?

35:39.111 --> 35:41.394
Never even think about God.

35:41.414 --> 35:45.799
Maybe days or weeks or months.

35:47.722 --> 35:50.165
Never even think about God.

35:50.185 --> 35:52.928
You know anybody like that?

35:52.948 --> 35:55.551
You know anybody like that if I said, hey, tell me about your prayer life.

35:56.572 --> 35:57.714
You'd rather change the subject.

35:59.276 --> 36:00.597
You know anybody like that in your life?

36:00.637 --> 36:02.580
I go, hey, tell me about your time in God's Word.

36:02.600 --> 36:04.562
What's that time just you and your Bible?

36:04.642 --> 36:11.952
when no one else is around, not in prep for a Bible study, not in prep for anything, but just you and your Bible.

36:13.034 --> 36:14.436
Tell me about what that's like for you.

36:14.857 --> 36:18.281
Tell me about how you live and what drives you.

36:19.403 --> 36:26.673
And is it possible that maybe King Saul is a bit of a mirror for us because we're just like him?

36:27.935 --> 36:32.722
And could it be possible if that's the case that God put King Saul in your life

36:33.570 --> 36:35.493
to kill the king's soul that's in you.

36:37.036 --> 36:38.258
See, why are these stories here?

36:39.620 --> 36:47.393
These stories are here for our instruction that we might learn the lessons of those who've gone before without having to pay their dumb tax.

36:47.413 --> 36:48.515
They paid it for us.

36:49.516 --> 36:50.658
This guy pays a price.

36:50.758 --> 36:52.401
I hope none of us ever have to pay.

36:52.702 --> 36:53.262
But you know what?

36:53.283 --> 36:54.144
We're just like him.

36:55.286 --> 36:55.987
We don't pray.

36:56.348 --> 36:57.530
We don't read our Bibles.

36:57.770 --> 37:00.274
We live life based on instinct, gut,

37:00.386 --> 37:06.614
drive metrics, what feels right, the latest podcast we just listened to, that's what's informing our life.

37:06.654 --> 37:16.647
And it is very common for us to just live in flesh, to just do life based on our own logic, our own wisdom, our own earthly skill set.

37:17.268 --> 37:20.271
And if that's you, I just said, I think God has more for you.

37:21.072 --> 37:28.562
Because the beauty of the gospel is he's actually redeemed us from autonomy and reconciled us to God

37:29.026 --> 37:34.574
Through Christ, by His Spirit, and therefore, we don't have to be in autonomy anymore.

37:34.814 --> 37:38.660
Now you will always, like so, have a bent, as I do, towards autonomy.

37:39.421 --> 37:39.621
Why?

37:39.782 --> 37:40.643
It comes natural.

37:41.664 --> 37:43.948
But we've been invited not to live in autonomy.

37:44.268 --> 37:46.071
We've been invited to actually be in spirit.

37:46.872 --> 37:48.274
And to be in spirit, that's different.

37:49.175 --> 37:50.898
And that's going to require some retraining.

37:51.619 --> 37:53.261
That's going to require some relearning.

37:53.922 --> 37:56.626
And that's going to require us developing a skill set

37:56.898 --> 37:59.362
that right now might be undeveloped.

37:59.903 --> 38:08.096
But the alternative is, if we don't develop it, we end up functioning just like Saul, just in the flesh, just in autonomy.

38:08.817 --> 38:12.543
And all the consequences of that are catastrophic, aren't they?

38:12.563 --> 38:20.636
So what might it be for us as the people of God to learn the lessons of those who've gone before, that by God's grace, we don't have to repeat their insanity.

38:20.976 --> 38:24.301
But instead, we can learn to submit to the king of kings who loves us.

38:24.381 --> 38:24.722
Amen?

38:25.666 --> 38:26.667
Well, Father, we're grateful.

38:26.707 --> 38:29.190
Thank you for the privilege that we have to be in Christ.

38:29.911 --> 38:33.635
And in that, to be those who aren't stuck in autonomy any longer.

38:34.456 --> 38:36.638
And so Lord, may your Bible be rich in our life.

38:37.299 --> 38:39.481
May our time and prayer be life-giving also.

38:40.042 --> 38:43.285
That we would reject leading and living in the flesh.

38:44.166 --> 38:49.332
And know in the wisdom that this world has to offer, but instead, God, we'd embrace the mystery of life with you.

38:49.953 --> 38:54.898
So bless us as we respond a bit and worship here as we sing and celebrate as a community.

38:54.978 --> 38:56.213
May you be honored by it all.

38:56.233 --> 38:57.955
Well, thank you in Jesus name.

38:57.975 --> 38:58.258
Amen.

